C. Data Preprocessing

Handle Missing Values

For Numeric Variable, use median value

num_cols <- sapply(data, is.numeric)
for(col in names(data)[num_cols]){
  data[[col]][is.na(data[[col]])] <- median(data[[col]], na.rm = TRUE)
}

For Categorical Variable, use mode value

cat_cols <- sapply(data, is.character)
get_mode <- function(x){
  ux <- na.omit(unique(x))
  ux[which.max(tabulate(match(x, ux)))]
}
for(col in names(data)[cat_cols]){
  data[[col]][is.na(data[[col]])] <- get_mode(data[[col]])
}

Remove duplicate variable 

data<-data[!duplicated(data), ]
cat("\nMissing values after handle missing values and remove duplicate values:\n")

One-hot coding

One-hot encoding converts categorical variables into numeric binary columns, where each category is represented by a separate column with 0 or 1 values

data<-dummyVars(" ~ .",data=data) %>% predict(newdata=data) %>% as.data.frame()

Salling

Scaling standardizes numeric variables so that each has a mean of 0 and a standard deviation of 1

data_scaled<-scale(data)

Skewness

Skewness correction identifies numeric variables that are highly skewed (skewness > 1) and applies a log transformation to reduce skewness

skewed<-apply(data_scaled,2,function(x) abs(e1071::skewness(x))>1)
data_scaled[, skewed] <- log1p(abs(data_scaled[, skewed]))

PCA

PCA transforms the data into a smaller set of uncorrelated components that capture most of the variance

pca_res<-prcomp(data_scaled,scale.=TRUE)
fviz_eig(pca_res)
## Warning in geom_bar(stat = "identity", fill = barfill, color = barcolor, :
## Ignoring empty aesthetic: `width`.

Selects the first four principal components from the PCA results to use for clustering 

pc_data<-pca_res$x[, 1:4]

Within-cluster sum of squres

Code computes the total within-cluster sum of squares (WSS) for different numbers of clusters (k = 1 to 20) to help determine the optimal number of clusters using the Elbow Method

wss<-c()
for(k in 1:20){
  set.seed(123)
  km_model<-kmeans(pc_data,centers=k,nstart=25)
  wss[k]<-km_model$tot.withinss
}

Elbow Method

This plot visualizes the total within-cluster sum of squares (WSS) for different numbers of clusters. The elbow point helps identify the optimal number of clusters for K-means

plot(1:20,wss,type="b",pch=19,
     xlab="Number of clusters (k)",
     ylab="Total Within-Cluster Sum of Squares",
     main="Elbow Method for K-means")

Best K based on Silhoute score

Code calculates the average silhouette score for different numbers of clusters (k = 2 to 20) to evaluate cluster quality. The number of clusters with the highest silhouette score is chosen as the best k for K-means

sil_scores<-c()
for(k in 2:20){
  set.seed(123)
  km_model<-kmeans(pc_data,centers=k,nstart=25)
  sil<-silhouette(km_model$cluster,dist(pc_data))
  sil_scores[k]<-mean(sil[,3])
}

sil_scores<-sil_scores[2:20]
best_k<-which.max(sil_scores)+1
cat("Best K based on silhouette score:",best_k, "\n")
## Best K based on silhouette score: 14

Silhouette Analysis 

plot(2:20, sil_scores, type="b", xlab="Number of clusters (k)", 
     ylab="Average Silhouette Score", main="Silhouette Analysis")

D. Modeling

k-means clustering 

set.seed(123)
final_km<-kmeans(pc_data,centers=best_k,nstart=50)

E.Evaluation

Average silhoutte score 

final_sil <- silhouette(final_km$cluster, dist(pc_data))
cat("Average silhouette score for final model:", mean(final_sil[,3]), "\n")
## Average silhouette score for final model: 0.5724904

Evaluation with cluster plot 

plot(pc_data[,1], pc_data[,2], col=final_km$cluster, pch=19,
     xlab="PC1", ylab="PC2", main=paste("K-means Clusters (k =", best_k, ")"))
legend("topright", legend=paste("Cluster", 1:best_k), col=1:best_k, pch=19)
